summary: I'm a food designer working with cheese. My background is in fine arts and design, product and interior design. Thirteen years ago, I discovered I could make cheese at home and fell in love with cheese making. Today I run De Kaasserie, a platform meant to promote and explore the craft of making cheese. At De Kaasserie workshops are offered and artisanal cheese making tools are made available for people to explore the history of cheese making and to experiment with the cheese that can make today. Creative cheese making is about this exploration, creating a complete experience around cheese making, which is meant to inspire and empower.

[{'title': "Futurotextiles'12 CETI Innovation in Textile Award", 'description': "The CETI prize - High Technology in textile innovation awarded to José Subero and Paula Colchero for the project LOOP, an urban seat made from high-performance textile ribbons and stitches.The prize was unanimously awarded by a jury presided by designers Matali Crasset and Fréderic Ruyant in the context of Futurotextiles'12. An international competition aimed to promote textile innovation, the use of new flexible and composite materials and to stimulate connections between designers and the textile industry in the North of France.", 'issuer': 'Centre Européen des Textiles Innovants & Lille Design - France', 'date': {'month': 10, 'day': None, 'year': 2012}}, {'title': 'First Prize Air France Meal Set Design competition', 'description': "Paula Colchero and Sabine Marcelis were awarded the first prize for Picnic, a meal set that communicates french identity, while improving the passenger's experience and  considerably reducing the amount of waste produced in it's use.

In May 2009 Air France and KLM launched their first Young Designers Competition aimed at students and recent graduates from design schools in France, the Netherlands, Belgium, Great Britain, Switzerland and Italy.  

Winning designs were chosen for their creativity, originality and aesthetics, and whether they were environmentally friendly, technical feasible and economically sound.

Entrants were asked to create and revamp the concept of the meal tray and associated tableware, such as plates, containers, glasses and cutlery, intended for the Business class cabin the Premium Voyageur cabin and Voyageur economy class on Air France and KLM medium- and long-haul flights.
